’җҗЪқTitle: title: polars truncate
Path: Examples
Content:
Truncate a series of dates by period length
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> seq date -b 2025-01-01 --periods 4 --increment 6wk -o "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S" | polars into-df | polars as-datetime "%F %H:%M:%S" --naive | polars select datetime (polars col datetime | polars truncate 5d37m | polars as truncated)
в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
в”Ӯ # в”Ӯ   datetime    в”Ӯ   truncated   в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Ө
в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ a year ago    в”Ӯ a year ago    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ a year ago    в”Ӯ a year ago    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ a year ago    в”Ӯ a year ago    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ 11 months ago в”Ӯ 11 months ago в”Ӯ
в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ


```
—ЩWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/commands/docs/polars_truncate.mdЩ@9a35109265808282656a4648620e74e3ab33a38d8119422df06dbfbf4147dfe9¶title: polars truncate‘ҘNotesЪZEach date/datetime is mapped to the start of its bucket using the corresponding local datetime. Note that weekly buckets start on Monday. Ambiguous results are localised using the DST offset of the original timestamp - for example, truncating '2022-11-06 01:30:00 CST' by '1h' results in '2022-11-06 01:00:00 CST', whereas truncating '2022-11-06 01:30:00 CDT' by '1h' results in '2022-11-06 01:00:00 CDT'.
```Indented
    See Notes in documentation for full list of compatible string values for `every`: https://docs.pola.rs/api/python/stable/reference/expressions/api/polars.Expr.dt.truncate.html
```
’җҗЪҚTitle: title: polars truncate
Path: Notes
Content:
Each date/datetime is mapped to the start of its bucket using the corresponding local datetime. Note that weekly buckets start on Monday. Ambiguous results are localised using the DST offset of the original timestamp - for example, truncating '2022-11-06 01:30:00 CST' by '1h' results in '2022-11-06 01:00:00 CST', whereas truncating '2022-11-06 01:30:00 CDT' by '1h' results in '2022-11-06 01:00:00 CDT'.
```Indented
    See Notes in documentation for full list of compatible string values for `every`: https://docs.pola.rs/api/python/stable/reference/expressions/api/polars.Expr.dt.truncate.html
```
